The paper deals with graph algorithms and their applications in real-world networks, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The concept of extremal-distance spanners is a fundamental topic in graph theory, which is closely related to network analysis and optimization, indicating that it could also fit into the cs.NE (Networks and Internet Architecture) category. The paper also involves geometric and combinatorial arguments, which are typical of the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) categories. Finally, the paper discusses dynamic and fault-tolerant settings, which are relevant to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) category.
